response:
 There are 6 forks, 6 spoons, and 6 knives, making a total of 18 silver tools. The number of ways of choosing 3 among 18 is
\begin{align*}
_{18}\mathbf{C}_{3} &= \frac{18!}{3!(18-3)!}\\
&= \frac {18\mathrm{\times} 17\mathrm{\times} 16}{3\mathrm{\times} 2\mathrm{\times}  1}\\
&= 2\mathrm{\times} 17\mathrm{\times} 16 = 204.
\end{align*}

Well the such a selection  this example contains exactly 1 (1st) paste, 1 (2nd) spoon & 1 (3rd) knife, i.e., the three items are selected without placing them to the main selection.

Therefore T1 =  consider the such permutations with this 3 items were correlated. The number of permutations of 3 items is
\begin{align*}
_{3}\mathbf{P}_{3} &= 3! = 3\times 2 \times 1 = 6.
\end{align*}

T2 =  consider  three  items as a group where  they can be permuted  within  itself=  for example, one set of such permutations is in the form [F, S, K], where F is a fork, S is spoons, & K represents a knife.

Therefore the number of such permutations for a group of three items in this way = the number of permutations of a word of 3 distinct letters, which is 3.
\begin{align*}
_{3}\mathbf{P}_{3} &= 3! = 3\times 2 \times 1 = 6.
\end{align*}

So,  a total number = the number of selecting three items in all * number of permutations within the three items = 204 * 6 = 1224.

